      <memberdef kind="define" id="group__devicetree-generic-vendor_1gae4bbd66726d930d878588f9bb9f4d500" prot="public" static="no">
        <name>DT_NODE_MODEL_BY_IDX</name>
        <param><defname>node_id</defname></param>
        <param><defname>idx</defname></param>
        <initializer>	DT_CAT3(node_id, _COMPAT_MODEL_IDX_, idx)</initializer>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Get the model at index &quot;idx&quot; as a string literal. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>The model is a string extracted from the compatible after the vendor prefix.</para>
<para>Example vendor-prefixes.txt: <verbatim> vnd        A stand-in for a real vendor
 zephyr     Zephyr-specific binding
</verbatim> Example devicetree fragment: <verbatim> n1: node-1 {
    compatible = &quot;vnd,model1&quot;, &quot;gpio&quot;, &quot;zephyr,model2&quot;;
 };
</verbatim> Example usage: <verbatim> DT_NODE_MODEL_BY_IDX(DT_NODELABEL(n1), 0) // &quot;model1&quot;
 DT_NODE_MODEL_BY_IDX(DT_NODELABEL(n1), 2) // &quot;model2&quot;
</verbatim> Notice that the compatible at index 1 doesn&apos;t match any entries in the vendor prefix file and therefore index 1 is not a valid model index. Use <ref refid="group__devicetree-generic-vendor_1ga2ff3c91b22fae081d00d96964f465aa2" kindref="member">DT_NODE_MODEL_HAS_IDX(node_id, idx)</ref> to determine if an index is valid.</para>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>node_id</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>node identifier </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>idx</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>index of the model to return </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>string literal of the idx-th model </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
